{"questionId":"14859745","questionHtml":"<p>The following table shows the probability distribution of a discrete random variable&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>X</mi><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/88dbca3cddfe39c1ef4065f1c52f9e23f847add3.png\"></p>\n<p>Given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mfenced><mi>X</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></math>, find the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The first two <em><strong>A</strong></em> marks are independent of each other.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong>&nbsp;(finding intersections of functions)</p>\n<p>attempt to make <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math> the subject in both of their equations&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;</strong></em>and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>use of graph or table to attempt to find intersection&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong> (solving algebraically)</p>\n<p>attempt to solve their equations algebraically to find a cubic in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)</p>\n<p>attempt to solve their cubic in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp;(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>552839</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp;</strong></em>OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>315870</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp;(other solutions to cubic are&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>18538</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86951</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>553</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note: </strong>If no working shown, award <em><strong>(A1)(A1)(M1)(M1)A0</strong></em> for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>44587</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp;<strong>OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8987</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;award<em><strong> (A0)(A0)(M1)(M1)A0 </strong></em>for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>55</mn></math>&nbsp;(2sf).</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"14859745","referenceCode":"23N.2.AHL.TZ2.5","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The following table shows the probability distribution of a discrete random variable X, where a, k∈ℝ+. Given that EX=2.3, find the value of a.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"5","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.7—Discrete random variables","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.10—Solving equations graphically and analytically"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}